{"to":["yourname@uniontrustbank.com"],"subject":"Re: Request for Customer Engagement Data Needed by MarketMinds","body":"Hi [Your Name],

Thanks for outlining the data MarketMinds needs.

I’ll open the “Marketing Analytics – 2024 > MarketMinds Data Requests” space this afternoon, double-check that the notes titled “Q1–Q2 Engagement Metrics” reflect our most current figures, and then pull the requested aggregates:
• Monthly new-account openings & closures (Jan–May 2024)
• Average customer tenure & churn rate for the same period
• Quarterly NPS trend (Q3 ’23 – Q2 ’24)
• Top 5 digital-banking features by usage (%)
• Active-customer demographics by age band & region

My plan is to export the dataset to .xlsx and place it in the secure ShareFile folder linked at the top of the page. I’ll send you a quick confirmation (or attach the file) once the upload is complete—well before end-of-day Thursday, 13 June.

If anything changes on your side—additional metrics, a different file format, etc.—just let me know.

Best regards,
Jane"}

formatted_items.content:
Thought process:

1. Identified the request asked me to acknowledge and commit to gathering specific aggregated metrics from Notion, then deliver them via ShareFile or email by 13 June.
2. Searched Notion for the “Q1–Q2 Engagement Metrics” page and the “MarketMinds Data Requests” parent space to verify I could locate the right workspace (both yielded a “Customer Engagement Data” page, indicating the needed content exists).
3. Confirmed there were no special Gmail threads under the same subject yet, so my reply would initiate/continue appropriate correspondence.
4. Drafted a concise confirmation email:
   • Restated each requested data set to show clear understanding.  
   • Communicated timeline commitment (“this afternoon” and “well before EOD 13 June”).  
   • Mentioned planned file type (.xlsx) and delivery via ShareFile, plus optional email attachment.  
   • Invited any adjustments to requirements.
5. Sent the reply to the requester’s email address using gmail_send_message, ensuring a professional tone and alignment with data-sharing policy (aggregated numbers only, no PII).
